{"id":"astro-ph/0401148","submitter":"Mario Tafalla","authors":"M. Tafalla (OAN), P.C. Myers (CfA), P. Caselli (Arcetri) and C.M.\n  Walmsley (Arcetri)","title":"On the internal structure of starless cores. I. Physical conditions and\n  the distribution of CO, CS, N2H+, and NH3 in L1498 and L1517B","comments":"A&A accepted. 23 pages, 15 figures. v2: Minor typos corrected. v3:\n  additional clarifications on turbulent models; final journal version","journal-ref":"Astrophys.Space Sci. 292 (2004) 347-354; Astron.Astrophys. 416\n  (2004) 191-212","doi":"10.1023/B:ASTR.0000045036.76044.bd","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We have characterized the physical structure and chemical composition of two\nclose-to-round starless cores in Taurus-Auriga, L1498 and L1517B. Our analysis\nis based on high angular resolution observations in at least two transitions of\nNH3, N2H+, CS, C34S, C18O, and C17O, together with maps of the 1.2 mm\ncontinuum. For both cores, we derive radial profiles of constant temperature\nand constant turbulence, together with density distributions close to those of\nnon-singular isothermal spheres. Using these physical conditions and a Monte\nCarlo radiative transfer model, we derive abundance profiles for all species\nand model the strong chemical differentiation of the core interiors. According\nto our models, the NH3 abundance increases toward the core centers by a factor\nof several while N2H+ has a constant abundance over most of the cores. In\ncontrast, both C18O and CS (and isotopomers) are strongly depleted in the core\ninteriors, most likely due to their freeze out onto grains at densities of a\nfew 10^4 cm^{-3}. Concerning the kinematics of the dense gas, we find (in\naddition to constant turbulence) a pattern of internal motions at the level of\n0.1 km s^{-1}. These motions seem correlated with asymmetries in the pattern of\nmolecular depletion, and we interpret them as residuals of core contraction.\nTheir distribution and size suggest that core formation occurs in a rather\nirregular manner and with a time scale of a Myr. A comparison of our derived\ncore properties with those predicted by supersonic turbulence models of core\nformation shows that our Taurus cores are much more quiescent than\nrepresentative predictions from these models.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 9 Jan 2004 13:44:57 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 2 Feb 2004 12:38:22 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 16 Feb 2004 09:59:34 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-10"}
